 '''Todd D. Stern''' (born May 4, 1951) served as the [[United States]] Special Envoy for Climate Change, leading talks at the [[United Nations climate change conference]]s and smaller sessions, appointed by U.S. Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]] on January 26, 2009.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2009/01/26/stern_appointed_climate_change.html?hpid=topnews | title = Stern Appointed Climate Change Envoy | first = Garance | last = Franke-Ruta | work = [[The Washington Post]] | date = January 26, 2009 | access-date = January 27, 2009 }}</ref> He was the United States' chief negotiator at the 2015 [[Paris Agreement|Paris Climate Agreement]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2015/12/12/statement-president-paris-climate-agreement|title=Statement by the President on the Paris Climate Agreement|date=December 12, 2015|via=[[NARA|National Archives]]|work=[[whitehouse.gov]]|access-date=July 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/secretary/remarks/2016/03/254872.htm |title=Statement on the Departure of U.S. Special Envoy for Climate Change Todd Stern and the Appointment of Jonathan Pershing |last=Kerry |first=John |date=March 21, 2016 |website=U.S. Department of State |access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>

-Stern previously served under the [[Bill Clinton]] administration as Assistant to the President and [[Staff Secretary]] in the White House from 1993 to 1998, during which time he also acted as the senior White House negotiator at the [[Kyoto Protocol]] and Buenos Aires negotiations.{{cn|date=December 2014}}
+Stern previously served under the [[Bill Clinton]] administration as Assistant to the President and [[Staff Secretary]] in the White House from 1993 to 1998, during which time he also acted as the senior White House negotiator at the [[Kyoto Protocol]] and Buenos Aires negotiations.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}

 ==Biography==
 Stern graduated from [[Dartmouth College]] in 1973,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://thedartmouth.com/2009/01/27/news/stern/ | title = Stern '73 to be climate-change envoy | first = Anya | last = Peret | work = [[The Dartmouth]] | date = 2009-01-27 | access-date = 2009-01-27 }}</ref> and earned a J.D. at [[Harvard Law School]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/health/article/0,8599,1874152,00.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130100434/http://www.time.com/time/health/article/0,8599,1874152,00.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=January 30, 2009 | work=Time | title=Climate Change Envoy Todd Stern | date=2009-01-26 | access-date=2010-05-25 | first=Frances | last=Romero}}</ref>

 ===E-8===
 He has proposed the creation of the E-8, a novel international group uniting leading developed nations and developing ones for an annual gathering focused on combating global warming.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2009/01/26/stern_appointed_climate_change.html?hpid=topnews | work=The Washington Post | access-date=2010-05-25 | title=Stern Appointed Climate Change Envoy}}</ref>

